It appeared after a brief rainy period followed by about 2 weeks of 20-23DegC weather.

results.notes:
Code: Bot_836/2012_DSC4012

Habitat: light mixed wood, Picea abies and Fagus sylvatica dominant, locally under canopies of dense stand of young Picea abies; in shade, no ground vegetations; moderately incline mountain slope, northwest aspect; calcareous ground; partly protected from direct rain by tree canopies; average precipitations ~ 3.000 mm/year, average temperature 4-6 deg C, elevation 935 m (3.070 feet), alpine phytogeographical region.

Substratum: soil covered by a layer of fallen off needles of Picea abies.

Place: Spodnja Trenta valley, next to the trail from Trenta village to Trebiški dol; about half way from Planina Krotica to Planina Lepoč, East Julian Alps, Posočje, Slovenia EC.

Comments: Ramaria longispora was originally described as a fungus of the Pacific Northwestern United States in 1973. For decades it hasn’t been recorded in Europe. However, Christan (2008) (Ref.2.) described it as present also in Europe in 2008. Also Hagar (2015) (Ref.:3.) is mentioning finds in Europe. Recently done mycological survey of the region of Triglav National Park, Slovenia revealed several finds in east Julian Alps (Ref.:4.). It has been found in four UTM sub-squares of this region so far.

The traits of this find fit well to literature. This species is macroscopically easy to confuse with small fruit bodies of Ramaria largentii. But Ramaria largentii has clamped basidia and hypha and somewhat smaller spores. I was unable to find clamps. Spore and basidia dimensions fit very well to literature, as well as relatively long sterigmata (average 8 microns). Also a few exceptionally long and deformed spores, which are characteristically produced by Ramaria longispora (Ref.:2) have been observed. One is shown on Picture 1M (arrow).

Growing solitary; fruit body dimensions: 6 cm tall and 3.5 cm wide; stipe solid, not branched up to 2.5 cm height and about 2 cm in diameter; SP faint, pale ocher-yellow, oac806 (?), color uncertain.

Nikon D700/Nikkor Micro 105mm/f2.8

results.notes: These are growing in a tiny patch of urban forest, on a tree, just 2 blocks from my house. The fungi is growing at the base of this tree and much higher up on the trunk. It is also growing on a couple of nearby trees, higher up, also on the trunk. I removed a small sample and noticed a embedded stick in the fungi. It seems another plant, growing near the trunk of this tree, grew near the fungi and the fungi started to feed on the plant, thus explaining the embedded stick. I do not know about the identification. However I believe this is a type of shelf/crust fungi. It is orange on the inside; firm to the touch, but breaks off easily; and has a very pleasant fragrance, similar to cedar (woody and slightly nutty).

results.notes:
I have often refered to this as Trametes cubensis, and have found it growing sessille, applanate to depressed, lignicolous, on decaying hardwood. Habitat is mixed coniferous/deciduous forest.

Similar characteristics amongst specimens I have observed is:

  • Young new species growing as a round, glaborous, basidiomata from gaps, cracks, and holes within substrate (especially through loose bark) with no clear pileus, margin, or hymenium. When taken off substrate, some young samples had pore tubes which were beginning to become visible.
  • White hymenium, yellowing or fading with age
  • Circular poroid surface separated by thick pore walls that enlarge with age
  • Single pore layer with light colored striations throughout context
  • A pileus composed of zonate bands varying in color from brownish to cream, whiting out or graying with age. However, I have observed amorphous growth, with no clear shelfing.
  • Smooth to bumpy glaborous pileus
  • Bruising brownish along the margin for fresh specimens
  • Pore surface may slightly bruise brownish when handled
  • Will leak moisture when wet
  • Growing as a single basidiomata or growing together into conjoined shelves
  • Sometimes effused-reflexed, expressing with a dimediate shelf
  • KOH reactions vary with no observable change to yellowing on pileus, pore surface, and context, of the light colored areas, and darkening of the browner areas.
  • Smell was fresh and airy; not of licorice or typical mushroom smell.
  • Mycellium is fibrous, white, and matted. I have observed it transfering from log into decayed hardwood along soil line, and possibly fruiting in a nearby log of the same tree; however, I have no way to determine if it was the same organism.
  • Trametes cubensis is described by Gomes-Silva, Ryvarden, Gibertoni as, “dimidiate basidiomata with reddish cuticle from the base” (2010). Or as, “Cap up to 8 × 15 × 2.5 em, sessile, applanate to effused-reflexed, white with reddish color at the base, cap becoming reddish with age, zonate, tomentose becoming glabrous, except

results.notes: These four pictures were all close together. The top picture with the ivory stipe is very mature. The middle two picture are of the same mushroom. The fourth tiny fungi is within maybe 10 inches of this observation. I can’t be sure it is the same fungi obviously, but we have very little showing right now, so I suspect it is. Three are close to each other, but the fourth is on the other side of a tidal influenced creek – so no way it is the same fungi. Gliophorus psittacina are close but there is not a hint of green on any of the fungi from the four sites just mentioned. The largest of the samples are bigger than a usual G.psittacina – over 5cm. results.notes:
This species was growing at the base of a Live Oak (Quercus virginiana) in a cultivated bed in front of the Ralph W. Steen Library. There were two specimens growing together, with a third, possibly aborted growth nearby. Though the bed was cultivated, I believe these were growing in relation to the roots of the tree.

Initial observation was listed as the following on the Mushroom Identification Forum (Facebook)

  • Yellow in color with yellow warts on pileus. Flat to undulating pileus that is yellow in color but darkening to brown at center
  • Stipe is yellow with clear striations visible along stipe
  • Delicate anulus around stipe showing white and yellow
  • Lamella are evenly spaced, close to crowded, and appear to be free of the stipe. White in color. Short gills present and various in length. Gills appear to be free
  • No large volva, even after digging into the ground
  • No bruising on stipe where I picked the body
  • Longitudinal striations above anulus

Upon cutting the second specimen I noticed:

  • That it’s stipe was yellowish fading to white
  • Slight yellow color on the gills
  • Yellow color unevenly distributed through context.

After taking the specimens home I observed:

  • No reaction to KOH
  • No bruising occurred throughout the course of the day and storage for one day in refrigerator
  • Pileipellis separated from context in a thin layer
  • NOTE: The photos I took at home were terrible. The lighting was to yellow and the lens I was using made it impossible to get clear overall shots.
